## Full structured response

### Diagnosis

The portaled `highlightLabelAnchor` renders at the **right edge of the viewport** because the CSS `transform: translate(calc(-100% - spacer), -50%)` that should shift it leftward silently becomes a no-op. Changing the anchor reference from the inner tick to the notch container (your attempted fix) adjusts the origin by ~12 px — invisible against a failure that leaves the label ~200 px in the wrong direction.

### Root Cause — AP-070 (extended)

> **`translate(-100%)` on a `position:fixed` div whose own box width is measured after a framer-motion child has already received an inline transform.**

In CSS, `translate(X%)` resolves `X%` against the **element's own rendered width**. For a `position:fixed` div, that width is determined by the shrink-to-fit algorithm (same as `position:absolute`): the browser must lay out the inner content to measure the content width, then use that as the div width.

The inner content is a `<motion.span>`. By the time the browser's containing-block width measurement pass runs, framer-motion has **already written `transform: translateX(4px)` as an inline style** on the span (it does this immediately on mount when `initial={false}` and `x: 4` is the animate target during the hidden state). Some browser layout engines treat a transformed inline-block as "out-of-flow for intrinsic sizing" — the containing div's measured width collapses to **0**. `translate(-100% - spacer)` = `translate(0 - spacer)` ≈ `translate(-8px)`. The anchor barely moves. The label renders at `left ≈ notch.left ≈ viewport right edge` and the text overflows rightward off-screen.

This is a deeper instance of **AP-070**: not "framer-motion overwrites your transform" but "framer-motion's transform on a child corrupts the parent's own-width measurement that a percentage transform depends on."

The fix removes any dependence on the element's own width. Use CSS `right` (distance from the viewport's right edge) instead of `left + translate(-100%)`:

| | Old | New |
|---|---|---|
| **JS** | `left: r.left` | `right: window.innerWidth - r.left + 8` |
| **CSS** | `transform: translate(calc(-100% - spacer), -50%)` | `transform: translateY(-50%)` |
| **SCSS guard** | _(none)_ | `width: max-content` |
| **`will-change`** | `top, left` | `top, right` |

`right = vw − notch.left + spacer` is the exact viewport-coordinate equivalent of the in-rail `.label`'s `right: calc(100% + spacer)` relative to the notch container. The label's right edge aligns with `notch.left − spacer` in both cases — same gutter, same stack, no width measurement required.

### Principle

**Never use `translate(N%)` when the element's own box size is determined by a child whose layout has already been mutated by JavaScript before the measurement pass.** The safe alternative is always to use the `right`/`bottom` CSS property directly (converting from `getBoundingClientRect()` viewport coordinates as needed). `right: X` pins the element's right edge at `X` from the viewport edge without touching the element's intrinsic size at all.
